Trappe will set off from Maine, USA, and set a course for Paris, France. But he will be at the mercy of the elements, and may land anywhere from Norway to North Africa, or be forced to abort and ditch into the ocean.

Four meteorologists will work around the clock from a command centre in Wyoming, USA, to help make sure Trappe arrives safely.

'Weather is the most important element of the whole crossing,' said Trappe.

'Two meterologists will focus on short term weather - what I'm facing immediately and helping to foresee danger or conditions that might put me into the ocean.

'The other two will focus on long term weather patterns, and my overall path to the other side.'

