He will take oxygen through tubes in his nose and wear a full oxygen mask once he reaches 25,000 feet.

'To climb I'll drop ballast such as sandbags,' he said. 'I'll be equipped with more food and water than I need so I can discard them too.'  

If something goes wrong, Trappe will change out of his UV protection suit into a cold water suit, pop enough balloons to bring the gondola close to the water, and attempt to land in the ocean.

'It would spell the end of the record attempt and could kill me,' he admitted.

'There will be no getting back into the air. But at least I'll be in a boat.'

Trappe's amazing adventure will be immortalised as a television documentary.

